{
  "The femur is classified as a:": "",
  "Long bone": "",
  "Flat bone": "",
  "Irregular bone": "",
  "Short bone": "",
  "The femur (thighbone) is classified as a long bone because it has a clearly defined diaphysis (shaft) that is longer than it is wide, along with two expanded epiphyses.": "",
  "Carpals of the wrist are classified as:": "",
  "Long bones": "",
  "Flat bones": "",
  "Sesamoid bones": "",
  "Short bones": "",
  "Carpal bones are short bones, roughly cube-shaped with nearly equal dimensions in length, width, and thickness, providing stability and allowing complex multi-directional movements of the wrist.": "",
  "The sternum is classified as a:": "",
  "The sternum (breastbone) is a flat bone that is thin and broad, providing protection for the heart and lungs while also serving as an important site for red blood cell production.": "",
  "Vertebrae are classified as:": "",
  "Irregular bones": "",
  "Vertebrae are irregular bones because they have complex shapes with multiple processes, facets, and foramina that do not fit into the long, short, or flat categories.": "",
  "The patella is classified as a:": "",
  "Sesamoid bone": "",
  "The patella (kneecap) is the largest sesamoid bone in the body, embedded within the quadriceps tendon to protect the knee joint and improve the mechanical advantage of the quadriceps muscle.": "",
  "Phalanges (finger and toe bones) are classified as:": "",
  "Long bones (miniature)": "",
  "Despite their small size, phalanges are classified as long bones because they have a shaft (diaphysis) and two ends (epiphyses), which is the defining structural characteristic of long bones.": "",
  "The scapula (shoulder blade) is classified as a:": "",
  "The scapula is a flat bone with a broad, triangular shape that provides a large surface area for muscle attachment and helps protect the posterior thorax.": "",
  "Which bone type is most important for hematopoiesis in adults?": "",
  "Long bones (diaphysis only)": "",
  "Flat bones such as the sternum and hip bones": "",
  "Flat bones contain significant amounts of red bone marrow in their spongy bone interior, making them the primary sites for blood cell production (hematopoiesis) in adults.": "",
  "The hip bone (os coxae) is classified as a(n):": "",
  "The hip bone is classified as irregular because it is formed by the fusion of three bones (ilium, ischium, and pubis) into a complex shape with multiple surfaces, projections, and foramina.": "",
  "The clavicle (collarbone) is classified as a:": "",
  "Long bone (modified)": "",
  "Despite its S-shaped curvature, the clavicle is classified as a modified long bone because it has a shaft and two ends, fulfilling the structural criteria of the long bone category.": "",
  "What is a long bone?": "",
  "A bone with a shaft (diaphysis) that is longer than it is wide, with expanded ends (epiphyses)": "",
  "Any bone found in the limbs regardless of shape": "",
  "A bone that is always large in size": "",
  "A bone that is flat and provides protection": "",
  "A long bone is defined by its shape rather than its absolute size. It has a diaphysis (shaft) that is longer than it is wide and two expanded epiphyses, and its primary function is providing leverage for movement.": "",
  "What is a short bone?": "",
  "A thin, plate-like bone that protects organs": "",
  "Any small bone in the body": "",
  "A bone that has stopped growing prematurely": "",
  "A roughly cube-shaped bone with nearly equal dimensions that provides stability and limited motion": "",
  "Short bones are approximately as wide as they are long, giving them a roughly cube-shaped appearance. They are found in the wrists (carpals) and ankles (tarsals) where they allow complex movements.": "",
  "What is a flat bone?": "",
  "A cube-shaped bone found in the wrist": "",
  "A bone that has been compressed by injury": "",
  "A thin, broad bone with parallel surfaces that provides protection and surface area for muscle attachment": "",
  "Any bone that is perfectly smooth on all surfaces": "",
  "Flat bones are thin and typically curved with broad surfaces. They consist of two layers of compact bone enclosing a layer of spongy bone (diploe) and serve to protect organs and provide attachment sites for muscles.": "",
  "What is a sesamoid bone?": "",
  "A small bone embedded within a tendon where it passes over a joint": "",
  "A bone that connects two other bones": "",
  "A bone that forms the skull sutures": "",
  "A type of bone found only in the spine": "",
  "Sesamoid bones are small, round bones that develop within tendons, typically where tendons cross joints. They protect the tendon from wear and improve the mechanical advantage of the associated muscle.": "",
  "What is an irregular bone?": "",
  "A bone with a complex shape that does not fit into the long, short, or flat categories": "",
  "A bone with an unpredictable number of surfaces": "",
  "A bone that formed abnormally due to disease": "",
  "Any bone that varies in size between individuals": "",
  "Irregular bones have complex shapes with multiple projections, foramina, or surfaces that prevent them from being classified as long, short, or flat. Examples include vertebrae, the mandible, and the hip bones.": "",
  "What does the term 'sutural bone' (Wormian bone) mean?": "",
  "A small, irregular extra bone that forms within the sutures of the skull": "",
  "A bone that forms from a tendon under stress": "",
  "A bone used surgically to repair skull fractures": "",
  "A bone fragment resulting from a comminuted fracture": "",
  "Sutural (Wormian) bones are small, irregular bones that form within the fibrous sutures between cranial bones. Their number and size vary from person to person and they are not counted in the standard 206 bones.": "",
  "What is the diploe?": "",
  "The marrow cavity inside a long bone": "",
  "The spongy bone layer sandwiched between two layers of compact bone in flat bones": "",
  "The joint surface cartilage on irregular bones": "",
  "The growth plate between the epiphysis and diaphysis": "",
  "The diploe is the internal layer of spongy bone found between the inner and outer tables of compact bone in flat bones, particularly the cranial bones. It contains red marrow and helps absorb impact forces.": "",
  "What does it mean for a bone to function as a lever?": "",
  "The bone stores and releases minerals on demand": "",
  "The bone absorbs shock during impact": "",
  "The bone acts as a rigid bar that amplifies the force or range of motion produced by muscle contraction at a joint": "",
  "The bone directly contracts to produce movement": "",
  "Long bones in particular function as levers in the musculoskeletal system. Muscles pull on bones at joints (fulcrums) to produce movement, and the length and shape of the bone determine the mechanical advantage of the lever.": "",
  "What is the hyoid bone?": "",
  "A U-shaped irregular bone in the neck that does not articulate with any other bone": "",
  "A flat bone in the cranial vault": "",
  "A sesamoid bone embedded in the throat muscles": "",
  "A short bone in the cervical spine": "",
  "The hyoid bone is a unique U-shaped irregular bone in the anterior neck that is the only bone in the body not articulating directly with another bone. It is suspended by muscles and ligaments and supports the tongue and larynx.": "",
  "What does it mean for ribs to be classified as flat bones?": "",
  "They are perfectly flat with no curvature": "",
  "They are short and cube-shaped": "",
  "They are irregularly shaped with multiple processes": "",
  "They are thin, curved bones with broad surfaces that protect thoracic organs": "",
  "Although ribs are curved, they are classified as flat bones because they are thin with broad surfaces. The term 'flat' refers to their thin, plate-like cross-section rather than their overall curvature.": "",
  "A radiologist reviews an X-ray of a patient who fell and notices a fracture in one of the small, cube-shaped bones of the wrist. Which bone classification has been fractured?": "",
  "A sesamoid bone": "",
  "A long bone": "",
  "A flat bone": "",
  "A short bone": "",
  "The carpal bones of the wrist are short bones. A common example is a scaphoid fracture, which is one of the most frequently fractured carpal bones due to its position during a fall on an outstretched hand.": "",
  "A hematologist needs to perform a bone marrow biopsy to evaluate a patient's blood cell production. She chooses the iliac crest (hip bone) as the biopsy site. Why is a flat bone an ideal choice for this procedure?": "",
  "Flat bones have the thinnest compact bone walls": "",
  "Flat bones are the easiest to access surgically": "",
  "Flat bones heal faster after biopsy than other bone types": "",
  "Flat bones contain abundant red marrow for hematopoiesis throughout life": "",
  "Flat bones like the iliac crest retain significant amounts of active red bone marrow throughout adulthood, making them ideal for marrow biopsies to evaluate blood cell production.": "",
  "A physical education teacher notices a runner complaining of knee pain at the front of the knee. An imaging study reveals inflammation around a small bone embedded within the quadriceps tendon. Which type of bone is causing the problem?": "",
  "A sesamoid bone (the patella)": "",
  "An irregular bone": "",
  "The patella is the largest sesamoid bone in the body, embedded within the quadriceps tendon. Inflammation of or around the patella is common in runners and results from repetitive stress on this sesamoid bone.": "",
  "A forensic anthropologist discovers a bone fragment at a crime scene. It is broad, thin, has two tables of compact bone with spongy bone in between, and appears to be curved. What type of bone is this most likely from?": "",
  "A flat bone like a cranial bone or rib": "",
  "A sesamoid bone like the patella": "",
  "A long bone like the tibia": "",
  "A short bone like a tarsal": "",
  "The description of two compact bone tables with spongy bone (diploe) between them and a broad, thin, curved shape is characteristic of flat bones, such as cranial bones or ribs.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a vertebra and notices it has a body, a vertebral foramen, transverse processes, and a spinous process. She wonders why it is not classified as a flat bone. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Its complex shape with multiple projections and foramina makes it irregular": "",
  "It is part of the axial skeleton, which only has irregular bones": "",
  "It is too small to be a flat bone": "",
  "It contains too much spongy bone": "",
  "Vertebrae are classified as irregular bones because their complex three-dimensional shape, including processes, facets, and foramina, does not fit the criteria for long, short, or flat bone categories.": "",
  "An orthopedic surgeon explains to a patient that their fracture in the femoral shaft will heal differently than a fracture in the calcaneus. What is the primary reason different bone types fracture and heal differently?": "",
  "Short bones cannot heal at all after a fracture": "",
  "Long and short bones have the same healing process, so the surgeon is incorrect": "",
  "Only long bones have a periosteum that aids in healing": "",
  "Different bone types have different proportions of compact and spongy bone, blood supply patterns, and mechanical loads that affect fracture patterns and healing rates": "",
  "Each bone type has a unique proportion of compact vs. spongy bone, distinct blood supply patterns, and different mechanical demands. These factors influence how fractures occur, how calluses form, and how quickly healing takes place.": "",
  "A pediatrician evaluates a newborn and notes an unusually high number of small bones along the skull suture lines on imaging. The parents are concerned. What should the doctor explain about these bones?": "",
  "These are fractured skull fragments that need surgery": "",
  "These are sutural (Wormian) bones, which are normal anatomical variants that form within skull sutures": "",
  "These bones indicate a calcium deficiency": "",
  "These are sesamoid bones that have formed in the wrong location": "",
  "Sutural (Wormian) bones are small, irregular extra bones that form within the sutures of the skull. They are generally considered normal anatomical variants, though a large number may sometimes be associated with certain genetic conditions.": "",
  "A patient reports chronic ankle instability after multiple sprains. The physician orders imaging and discovers that a sesamoid bone has developed within the peroneal tendon near the ankle. The patient is surprised bones can form in tendons. How should the physician explain this?": "",
  "A bone fragment from a previous fracture migrated into the tendon": "",
  "Calcium from the diet deposited randomly in the tendon": "",
  "This is a tumor that needs immediate removal": "",
  "Sesamoid bones naturally develop in tendons subjected to friction and mechanical stress to protect the tendon": "",
  "Sesamoid bones develop within tendons where they experience repeated friction and stress, particularly where tendons cross joints. They form to protect the tendon from wear and improve the mechanical advantage of the associated muscle.": "",
  "A nursing student is asked to identify why the skull bones of the cranium are classified as flat rather than irregular. What is the distinguishing characteristic?": "",
  "Cranial bones are thin plates with two layers of compact bone sandwiching spongy bone (diploe), fitting the flat bone pattern": "",
  "Cranial bones contain no spongy bone": "",
  "Cranial bones have a uniform thickness throughout": "",
  "Cranial bones are round, so they cannot be irregular": "",
  "Cranial bones have the characteristic flat bone structure of two thin layers of compact bone (inner and outer tables) with a spongy bone layer (diploe) sandwiched between them, distinguishing them from irregular bones.": "",
  "During a clinical anatomy lab, a student is handed an unknown bone that is U-shaped and does not articulate with any other bone. The instructor says it is the only bone in the body with this property. Which bone is it, and what classification does it belong to?": "",
  "The stapes, classified as a short bone": "",
  "The patella, classified as a sesamoid bone": "",
  "The hyoid, classified as an irregular bone": "",
  "The coccyx, classified as a flat bone": "",
  "The hyoid bone is a U-shaped irregular bone located in the anterior neck. It is unique because it is the only bone in the body that does not directly articulate with another bone, instead being suspended by muscles and ligaments.": ""
